permissions/licensing, please go to: www.TorontoStarReprints.comGTAAccused serial killer stands trial in first two of four Toronto shooting murdersThe killing of 16-year-old Elijah Azavior is just one of four murders Jattori Williams, 22, is alleged to have committed in 2018 and 2019By Alyshah HashamCourts ReporterTue., Oct. 11, 2022timer2 min. readupdateArticle was updated Oct. 12, 2022Const. Eric Yu received a radio call about the sound of five or six gunshots and an injured person at an east Toronto building around 6:45 p.m. on Sept. 14, 2018. When he arrived at the Bellamy Road location minutes later, he found 16-year-old Elijah Azavior lying by a staircase, Yu testified Tuesday. The boy had been fatally shot twice in his torso and injured by another four bullets.This is just one of four murders Jattori Williams, 22, is alleged to have committed in 2018 and 2019. Williams is now on trial for the first-degree murder of Azavior, and the second-degree murder of Jago Anderson four days later. Next spring he will face another judge-alone trial on two more charges of first-degree murder and one of attempted murder dating back to October 2019. Williams and another man are accused of wounding a 16-year-old boy south of the Jane and Finch Mall and then going on a shooting spree in a Toronto Community Housing complex near Driftwood Avenue and Grandravine Drive. Delaunte Bryant, 24, and Eric Rowe, 20, were killed and homes were left riddled with bullet holes, the Star reported at the time.In September 2018 — when he would have been just a few months past his 18th birthday — Williams had access to various firearms, according to an agreed statement of facts read in court Tuesday. On Sept. 12, 2018, he possessed a firearm possibly manufactured by Smith &amp; Wesson. He also possessed the gun used to shoot Azavior hours after the shooting took place, according to the facts read out in court by Crown prosecutor Rob Fried.It is agreed that the person who shot Azavior got out of an SUV along with another armed person. Anderson — who the Crown alleges was later murdered by Williams — was the driver of the SUV, according to the facts.A witness to the shooting described seeing a few people standing outside a variety store on Bellamy Road. He saw two of the people had guns — he initially thought they could have been playing with water guns — and saw them surround a boy. He then heard gunshots and saw smoke coming out of the one gun he could see.The two men or boys, who were wearing bandanas, got into the back doors of the car and the car drove away, the witness said.“I was very scared,” the man said, adding that he thought they might come into his car. He drove away as quickly as he could.“I was pretty shaken, I just accelerated to try and go fast.”Williams was arrested in June 2020. The trial continues. Alyshah Hasham is a Toronto-based reporter covering crime and court for the Star. Follow her on Twitter: @alysanmatiSHARE:Report an errorJournalistic StandardsAbout The StarJOIN THE CONVERSATION Q:Anyone can read Conversations, but to contribute, you should be a registered Torstar account holder. If you do not yet have a Torstar account, you can create one now (it is free)Sign InRegisterConversations are opinions of our readers and are subject to the Code of Conduct. The Star
